The two remaining pieces of @eq-timp-pieces form the design-imbalance term. Their orders are counted directly. Under proper MI centered at $\hat\theta_{\text{obs}}$, the displacement $\delta := \tilde\phi - \theta_0$ has $\mathbb{E}[\delta] = O(n^{-1})$, the MLE bias, and $\operatorname{Var}(\delta) = I_{\text{obs}}^{-1} = O(n^{-1})$. The factors $\alpha$ and $H_{\phi\phi}$ are both $O(n)$, extensive in $n_{\text{mis}}$. Hence
$$
\begin{aligned}
(A) &= \mathbb{E}[\delta]^\top\alpha = O(1), \\
(C) &= \tfrac12\operatorname{tr}\!\big(H_{\phi\phi}\, I_{\text{obs}}^{-1}\big) + O(n^{-1}) = O(1),
\end{aligned}
$$
two order-one pieces of opposite sign. Their leading parts cancel exactly when the missing and observed units share a conditioning-variable distribution. That case is MCAR. Under MAR the sum survives. It has the bivariate monotone closed form
$$
\begin{aligned}
(A)+(C) &\;=\; \frac{n_{\text{mis}}}{n_{\text{obs}}} \Big[\, 1 - \tfrac12 \operatorname{tr}\big(Q_{\text{mis}} Q_{\text{obs}}^{-1}\big) \Big] \\
&\quad + O(n^{-1}),
\end{aligned}
$$ {#eq-ac}
where $Q_{\text{mis}}$ and $Q_{\text{obs}}$ are the conditioning-variable second-moment matrices of the missing and observed units. The term is zero exactly when the two distributions agree. For non-monotone patterns the covariance-MLE bias entering $(A)$ comes from the general second-order Cox-Snell bias of the MLE. We carry this bias to general dimension and verify it in two computer-algebra systems. Summing the pieces of @eq-timp-pieces with $\mathbb{E}[T_{\text{est}}]$ gives @eq-thm. These statements do not all rest on the same footing. The distinction matters for how the term is used. The structural facts are firm in the sense of @sec-methods. Its sign, its $O(1)$ order under MAR, its exact vanishing under MCAR, the closed form @eq-ac, and the information convention it is computed in are all proved. Its absolute magnitude is another matter. The per-replicate statistic is heavy-tailed. Direct Monte Carlo estimates therefore scatter without trend around the analytic leading-order value. The magnitude is measured only imprecisely. The saving fact is that comparisons never depend on the magnitude alone. Candidates fit to the same imputations touch $(A)+(C)$ only through their difference. The heavy-tailed component cancels in that difference. The comparison-relevant differential is derived and measured precisely in the next part.

